TITLE: Executing Terminal Commands Reliably with Shell Integration - VS Code Extension (TypeScript)
DESCRIPTION: This snippet shows how an extension can execute a terminal command using the shell integration API, which ensures the command is reliably executed and tracked. It first checks for shell integration support, uses the executeCommand method to run a command, and listens for the command's completion by comparing execution objects, printing the exit code when complete. If shell integration is missing, it falls back to sending text directly, with a comment indicating that command tracking is then unavailable. The code requires the shellIntegration capability and access to the terminal instance (term), with key parameters being the commandLine string and event.execution references.
SOURCE: https://github.com/microsoft/vscode-docs/blob/main/release-notes/v1_93.md#2025-04-23_snippet_7

LANGUAGE: TypeScript
CODE:
```
const commandLine = 'echo "Hello world"';
if (term.shellIntegration) {
    const execution = shellIntegration.executeCommand({ commandLine });
    window.onDidEndTerminalShellExecution(event => {
        if (event.execution === execution) {
            console.log(`Command exited with code ${event.exitCode}`);
        }
    });
} else {
    term.sendText(commandLine);
    // Without shell integration, we can't know when the command has finished or what the
    // exit code was.
}
```

